'''The Wellington Corpus of Spoken New Zealand English''' is a one-million-word corpus of transcribed English compiled from materials collected between 1988 and 1994, which is made up of excerpts from a range of speakers who have lived in [[New Zealand]] since before the age of 10. The corpus was collected under the direction of linguist [[Janet Holmes (linguist)|Janet Holmes]] and includes broadcast transcripts as well as informal conversations, telephone conversations, lectures, and oral history interviews.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://kh.hd.uib.no/icame/manuals/WSC/INDEX.HTM|title = Wellington Corpus|date = 1998|accessdate = May 28, 2015|website = |publisher = |last = Janet Holmes, Bernadette Vine and Gary Johnson, and Bernadette Vine|first = }}</ref>
The corpus, which was distributed as part of the 1999 [[ICAME]] CD-ROM, has been used for a number of academic studies including those looking at morphology,<ref>{{Cite book|title = New Zealand English Grammar: Fact or Fiction|last = Hundt|first = Marianne|publisher = John Bengjamins|year = 1998|isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref> pronoun use<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Generic pronouns in the Wellington Corpus of Spoken New Zealand English|journal = Kōtare: New Zealand Notes & Queries|date = 1998|website = |publisher = |last = Holmes|first = Janet}}</ref> and language contact studies, as of the influence of [[Māori language|Māori]] on NZ English.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Maori presence in the New Zealand English lexicon, 1850–2000: Evidence from a corpus-based study|last = Macalister|first = John|date = 2006|journal = English World Wide|doi = |pmid = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Trends in New Zealand English: Some Observations on the Presence of Maori Words in the Lexicon|last = Macalister|first = John|date = 1999|journal = New Zealand English Journal|doi = |pmid = }}</ref>
